    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Looking at converting some cython-syntax code to be valid python, what is one line in cython becomes much more verbose in pure-python mode:\r\n\r\n```\r\ncdef bint is_leapyear(int64_t year) nogil:\r\n\r\n@cython.nogil\r\n@cython.returns(bint)\r\n@cython.cfunc\r\ndef is_leapyear(year: int64_t):\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe decorators here could reasonably be condensed to something like `@cython.cfunc(nogil=True, returns=bint)`\r\n\r\n(ideally the `@cython.returns(bint)` could be specified python-style by `-> bint:`, but thats a separate issue)",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Yeah, the `@cython.returns()` isn't really needed any more, now that return type annotations can be used.\r\nThat reduces the gain to `@cython.cfunc(nogil=True)`. Is that still worth it?",
